@906  = ~Sir Ajantis never recovered from his betrothed's rise to godhood as an evil goddess. Struggling with his loss, as well as his own part in the happenings, he intensified his fighting for good and righteousness for the Order of the Radiant Heart, driving fear into many an evildoer alongside Faerûn. 

With Helm as his only guidance for his fights against evil, Sir Ajantis spent his time in stern silence. He lived several years in solitude, fighting and praying to Helm, but it was said that, through his sister, he finally found a way back to his family in Waterdeep. Words are that his parents offered him a place amongst them once again, and he was henceforth seen to visit them regularly. But never did he stay long, and never again did he call himself a son of Ilvastarr.

Many a young knight wanted to hear the tale about his travels with <CHARNAME> before <PRO_HISHER> ascension to godhood. If Sir Ajantis complied with the request, he told a sad and bitter tale about the inescapable destiny the gods bestow upon the mortals and the ever lasting struggle of one's own conscience against inner evil. Many a young knight left crestfallen after such a tale, and over the years, the pleas for telling it diminished.

He died of old age, a bitter, silent knight of good and righteousness, calling Helm 'the only god worth praying to'. And yet, his last words, passed down by his last squire Sir Kenran, were said to be: 'By Helm! <CHARNAME>... my love.'~


//TextScreen("c#ajep07")
@907  = ~After the events of the Throne of Bhaal were over, Sir Ajantis returned to his Order of the Radiant Heart, called a hero, a savior by many. Struggling with his own doings of helping an evil god to rise, he fought many battles in the name of good and righteousness, driving fear into many an evildoer of Faerûn, using all the prowess he had gained at <CHARNAME>'s side. But he did so in silence, mediating with his only god Helm, and only few could tell to ever have heard Sir Ajantis' cheerful laugh.

Many a young knight wanted to hear the tale about his travels with <CHARNAME> before <PRO_HISHER> ascension to godhood. It took long years until Sir Ajantis could comply with this request without feelings of bitterness and grief.

There is not much knowledge about his private life, but it is said that he did not remain alone, but found a woman he married and proudly shared the name Ilvastarr with. Their marriage was blessed with children, and it was Sir Kenran, Sir Ajantis' last squire, who said in confidence that this family was the reason Sir Ajantis did not despair of life.

He died of old age, his name eternalized in the bards' tales about the ascension of <CHARNAME>, god of murder.~

